-1 NAMES~
Ahh yes, names, the things by which we identify ourselves and others. 
Here at Mystery, we prefer names to be of Fantasy/Medieval origin.  "Common"
names, like Bob, John or Mary are generally frowned upon, as are names which
are downright silly, such as "Squeeky", "WhiteyDaPimp", and "Crayon".  Also,
offensive or rude names are not allowed.  Race names are not allowed either,
so you can't go around calling yourself "Cattain" or "Gold Dragon", whether
you are or are not one of that particular race. Names cannot contain
more than one capital letter.
 
Try to keep in mind that you're trying to come up with a name, not an
adjective or anything of that sort.  Words like Demonic or Fluffy and
so on are not acceptable. Neither are names like "Dog" or "Jaguar".

Seems like a lot that we don't allow, eh? Yeah, well, we're selective. In
order to foster a good role-play environment, we felt it necessary to weed
out the silly, irrelevant, and such names, to better improve the In Character
atmosphere.

When you first create, you will have a (NEWBIE) flag assigned to you. 
If your name is found to be acceptable by the Immstaff, then the flag will be
removed. Should you be informed that you must recreate with a different name,
please comply. Arguing just exacerbates the situation. However, if you feel 
you have a valid Role-Play reason to have that particular name, explain it to
the Immortal, and if they agree, there's a good chance your name will pass.
 
If you just can't seem to think of anything, there are webpages that offer 
name generators for player character names. The addresses are:
http://www.flatearth.com/utilities/name_generator.html
http://spitfire.ausys.se/johan/names/
~

-1 'MAGIC SYSTEM'~
7th Era of Mystery features a magic system that is different from most ROM
MUDs.  

When a character chooses to begin life as a mage, he or she can customize
the spells the begin with, instead of purchasing spells in spell groups. 
During creation, the "spells" command will list all spells available,
and they can then be added with the "add" command just like other skills or
skill groups.  At the guildmaster, the "gain spells" command will list all
spells available, and they can be added with the gain command.  All spells
cost one train or creation point to gain initially.  

After creation, a player may choose to specialize in one school of magic. 
These schools are Alteration, Necromancy, Enchantment, Illusion, Elemental,
Elemental Earth, Elemental Air, Elemental Fire, and Elemental Water.  There
exist two other schools of magic, Universal and Divination, which cannot be
specialized in.  Instead of specializing, a character may choose to become a
wizard.  Wizards have an assortment of spells from all schools.  

Certain spells can be trained to higher casting levels.  Spells that are
stated as being "Level 0" cannot be improved.  All other spells may be
improved if you have the necessary prerequisite spells for improvement and
have practiced the spell up to a high level of learning.  Increasing a
spell's power can be expensive.  To find out the prerequisites for improving
a spell's casting level, consult the spell's help file.  All spells that can
be improved can potentially be increased up to Spell Level 5.  However, only
specialists can ever reach Spell Level 5, and they can only bring one spell
to that level.  A specialist may bring all other spells up to level 3.  A

Wizard or a General Elementalist may not learn any level 5 spells.  However,
these two groups of spellcasters may train all spells up to Spell Level 4.  

For more information, see HELP CAST, HELP MAGE, HELP NECROMANCER,
 HELP BARD, ...
~

-1 'DISLODGE'~
Syntax: dislodge <arrow>

DISLODGE is used to remove an arrow that has become lodged somewhere upon
one's body.  Dislodging an arrow can be a painful procedure and is generally
accompanied by some damage to the character.
~


-1 WILD MAGIC~
Wild Magic is the magic that runs freely through the world.  While most
spellcasters use controlled magic and mana sources to cast their spells,
some choose to attempt to control this raw form of magic.  Those that cast
with Wild Magic are called Wild Mages.

Wild Mages are in most aspects similar to normal mages.  They have access to
the same skills and the same spells.  They can specialize in schools of
magic, though they cannot choose the Necromancy school or the Enchantment
school.  They can gain higher Spell Levels of spells, though they cannot
attain Spell Level 5 in any spells.  Wild Mages are limited to only one spell
of Spell Level 4, though they can know multiple spells at Spell Level 3 or
lower.

Unlike normal mages, the effective character level that a Wild Mage casts at
is random.  Every time a Wild Mage casts a spell, he or she casts it as if
he or she were somewhere between ten character levels lower and ten
character levels higher than he or she actually is.  Further, every time a
Wild Mage casts a spell, there is a chance that he or she will bring about a
Wild Surge.  A Wild Surge is a surge of the random, uncontrolled magic that
the Wild Mage is trying to control.  The result of the Wild Surge is random,
and while sometimes beneficial to the Wild Mage, it can be extremely
dangerous if not deadly as well.

In addition to the above, Wild Mages gain access to the spell 'reckless
dweomer'.  This spell allows the Wild Mage to attempt to cast any spell,
whether or not the Wild Mage knows the spell he or she is trying to cast.
However, this spell very normally results in a Wild Surge instead of the
intended effect.  See 'help reckless dweomer' for more information.

To become a Wild Mage, one must select mage as their class and then opt for
Wild Mage during creation.  It should be noted that Wild Mages cannot be any
form of Lawful alignment.
~

